    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.4.26-29_0001" />

                                                                                                                            <fw type="curatorial">26</fw>

                <opener>
                                                                    <dateline>
                                                                        Carmel by the Sea
                                                                        California
                                                                        12 Oct. 1917.
                                                                    </dateline>

                    <salute>Dear Mr. Neihardt, &#8212;</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I am delighted to hear from President Wheeler's secretary that he has invited you to read at the University of California while you are in the vicinity on your reading tour. I want you to be my guest while you are there, and shall go up for the occasion. Mrs Howard and I want you to come down here also and visit us in our 
                    
                    <pb facs="nei.j4a.4.26-29_0002"/>
                    
                    very rough little cabin. We are taking a year off and I am doing some special work in which I <del><unclear>want</unclear></del><add>hope</add> you <del><unclear>to</unclear></del><add>will</add> be interested. I think it is going well &#8212; much the best thing I've done &#8212; but I shall value your judgment and comments more than I can say. I hope Mrs. Neihardt is coming with you. Please give my cordial greetings to her and the new &#8212; as well as the older &#8212; little Neihardts. I haven't made an opportunity <del>of</del><add>for</add> congratulating you on your <hi rend="caps">LL.D.</hi> I was 
    
                    <pb facs="nei.j4a.4.26-29_0003"/>
                                                                                                                            <fw type="curatorial">28</fw>

                    much pleased to hear of the well merited honor, but I am working <del>seven</del><add>four</add> or <del>eight</del><add>five</add> hours a day and letter writing comes hard. I value your last letter and read it over whenever I need a little friendly encouragement &#8212; I am impatient to hear &#8212; or read &#8212; more of the <title>Song of Three Friends.</title> Have you finished it yet? Please let me know when to expect you, and if there is anything you would specially like me to arrange for you &#8212; I wish, for the occasion of your visit, that 

                    <pb facs="nei.j4a.4.26-29_0004"/>
                                                                                                                                <fw type="curatorial">29</fw>
                
                    we were in Berkeley, but our house is leased for a year. I shall hope to put you up at the club if you are alone, or at some <add>other</add> pleasant place if, as I hope, Mrs. Neihardt accompanies you. In any case you are both to take the little side trip to this patch of chaparral.</p>
                <closer>
                                                    <salute>Always most cordially yours</salute>

                                                    <signed>J G Howard</signed>
                                                    <note type="curatorial">J<unclear>ohn</unclear> H<unclear>owar</unclear>d</note>
                </closer>

                <postscript>
                    <p>Please pay my respects to your mother and grandmother, also. Mrs Howard joins me in most cordially inviting both you &amp; Mrs Neihardt.</p>
                </postscript>
                
            </div1>
